Epoch:0 | TOPIC | Scientist0:Building on the earlier discussion, I’d like to deepen the exploration of our proposed stroke-based Latinized representation—particularly its theoretical grounding and practical implications for subword modeling in NMT. One critical angle we should consider is *how* this transformation preserves or enhances linguistic regularities inherent in Chinese characters.

Chinese characters are not arbitrary symbols; they’re structured compositions of strokes that follow standardized writing rules (e.g., 永's "eight principles of Yong"). By mapping strokes to a finite set of Latinized primitives—say, 'h' for horizontal, 's' for dot, 'p' for撇 (left falling), 'd' for捺 (right falling)—we effectively create a phonetically agnostic yet structurally informative sub-character alphabet. This allows BPE or Unigram-based subword tokenizers to identify recurring stroke n-grams across characters, potentially uncovering morpho-visual patterns invisible under character-level segmentation.

For instance, rare characters sharing stroke sequences with common ones (e.g., 過 → h-s-p-d-h-z-z; compare with 貫 → h-s-p-d-v-h) could benefit from shared subword units, improving generalization. More importantly, this approach may naturally support zero-shot translation for unseen characters by enabling the model to extrapolate from known stroke combinations—akin to how alphabetic systems handle novel word formations.

A key innovation lies in the **interoperability** of this representation: it doesn’t require modifying the NMT architecture. We can preprocess Chinese text into stroke sequences using existing stroke decomposition standards (e.g., Unicode IDS or GB13000 norms), then apply standard subword learning directly. Crucially, we can augment the sequence with positional or directional markers (e.g., p<sub>start</sub>, d<sub>end</sub>) or even layer in Pinyin alignment at training time to study whether multimodal cues (visual structure + phonetics) further boost disambiguation.

One challenge will be balancing fidelity and complexity: too many stroke categories hurt compressibility; too few lose discriminative power. We might explore ablation studies over stroke granularities (5-class vs. 8-class systems) and evaluate impact on segmentation efficiency and downstream BLEU scores.

Moreover, this method opens doors beyond translation—think cross-script information retrieval, handwriting recognition, or even aiding language learners through decomposed visual feedback. But staying focused on NMT, a compelling experiment would be testing low-resource Chinese dialect-to-English translation (e.g., Cantonese), where character coverage is sparser and OOV issues more severe.

In short, I propose we position this as a *structure-aware sub-character embedding strategy* that turns the logographic barrier into a compositional advantage—leveraging the systematicity of Chinese writing to make subword modeling more effective, interpretable, and scalable.
