Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The existing work on stroke-based modeling of Chinese characters—particularly StrokeNet—has demonstrated that decomposing characters into Latinized stroke sequences can alleviate both learning and parameter bottlenecks in NMT. However, these approaches typically treat stroke sequences as flat, linear strings without considering the hierarchical and topological structure inherent in how strokes combine to form radicals and characters. Moreover, while subword modeling benefits from shared vocabulary spaces, current Latinization schemes do not explicitly optimize for subword compatibility or linguistic regularity. My intuition is that a more structured, morphology-aware transformation of Chinese characters into Latinized stroke sequences—one that preserves not only stroke order but also spatial configuration and compositional hierarchy—can significantly enhance subword tokenization and cross-lingual transfer in NMT. By integrating principles from graph-augmented representation learning (as seen in Paper 2) and visual character modeling (Paper 3), we can design a system that maps characters into enriched, topology-preserving stroke sequences. This would allow subword models like SentencePiece or BPE to discover meaningful sub-character patterns across semantically or structurally related characters, thereby improving generalization, especially for rare or unseen characters. Unlike StrokeNet’s purely sequential mapping, this approach introduces structural awareness into the Latinization process, enabling better alignment with subword modeling assumptions. Furthermore, by incorporating stroke direction, positional relationships, and radical boundaries into the encoding scheme via symbolic modifiers (e.g., using diacritics or case-sensitive Latin letters), we create a richer, more differentiable input space that retains visual and morphological semantics. This idea diverges from prior art by not only representing strokes sequentially but also encoding their *relational geometry*, making it uniquely suited for integration with modern transformer-based architectures that benefit from fine-grained, interpretable inputs.

